# Convergence

Given a series $\sum_{n=1}^{\infty} a_n = a_1 + a_2 + \cdots$, let $s_n$ denote its $\spscript{n}{th}$ partial sum:
$$ s_n = \sum_{i=1}^n a_i = \inflate[+]{a}{n}\text{.} $$ 
If the sequence $\{s_n\}$ is convergent and $\xlimit{n}{\infty} s_n = s$ exists as a real number, then the series 
$\sum a_n$ is called **convergent** and we write
$$ \inflate[+]{a}{n} + \cdots = s\text{ or } \sum_{n=1}^{\infty} a_n = s\text{.} $$
The number $s$ is called the **sum** of the series. Otherwise, the series is **divergent**.
Furthermore, we state a series $\sum a_n$ is **absolutely convergent** if the series of absolute values 
$\sum \left|a_n\right|$ is convergent, and **conditionally convergent** if it is convergent but not absolutely convergent.

