## Limits to Infinity

If the series $\sum_{n=1}^{\infty} a_n$ is convergent, then $\xlimit{n}{\infty} a_n = 0$.

<div class="proof"> 

Let $s_n = \inflate[+]{a}{n}$. Then $a_n = s_n - s_{n-1}$. Since $\sum a_n$ is convergent, the sequence $\{s_n\}$ is convergent.
Let $\xlimit{n}{\infty} s_n = s$. Since $$ n - 1 \rightarrow \infty \text{ as } n \rightarrow \infty, $$ we also have 
$\xlimit{n}{\infty} s_{n-1} = s$. Therefore

$$\begin{align*}
  \xlimit{n}{\infty} a_n &= \xlimit{n}{\infty}(s_n - s_{n-1})                   \\
                         &= \xlimit{n}{\infty} s_n - \xlimit{n}{\infty} s_{n-1} \\
                         &= s - s = 0.
\end{align*}$$

</div>

