<section class="primary">

# Complex Series

The notion of a series is almost identically to that of real series, so only the differences are highlighted here.
Namely, the convergence or divergence of the infinite series $\sum_{j=1}^{\infty} z_j$ of complex numbers can
be formulated in terms of the convergence or divergence of two infinite series of real numbers. That is,
$$ s_n = \sum_{j=1}^n z_j = \sum_{j=1}^n x_j + i\sum_{j=1}^n y_j = \sigma_n + i\tau_n, $$
which implies that the infinite series $\sum_{j=1}^{\infty} z_j$ converges or diverges if and only if both
$$ \sum_{j=1}^{\infty} x_j \text{ and } \sum_{j=1}^{\infty} y_j $$ converge. Therefore, if $\sum z_j$ converges,
then $$ \sum_{j=1}^{\infty} z_j = \sum_{j=1}^{\infty} x_j + i \sum_{j=1}^{\infty} y_j. $$

